{"/service/ndnp/scu/batch_scu_figs_ver02/data/sn86063761/00516990831/1924040201/0349.xml":{"full_text":"Wi DEATU OF miS KLECKLEY.\nm v v\nV: Mrs. tula Jane Kleckley. nee\nRoof, was Born November 10, 1881, i\nand died March 30, 1924, making her\nsojourn on earth 42 year, 4 montths\nV1 and 20 days. February 11, 1905, she\n;f was married to V. B. Kleckley, and;\n\nM\nto this union two children were born\u00bb\nOne of whom preceded her to the\ngrave in infancy Her husband and\ndaughter survive hS*'. She leaves twd\nbrothers, sheriff E. A.- Roof and\nWillie F. Roof, l^xington; Mr*. Jfiiry\nSmith, Gilbert attd Mrs. IdaHsffhr\nthy, Ridge Spring, besides many rsla*\nm\n't\nNOTIC|: OF ELECTION,\nAll resident qualified electors pf the\nifVs. .-age of twenty one years in ll\\at por\n1\nI\nw\u2018.v\n\nW\\\nj? k\nt.on of Saint Andrews school district\nwhich was recently annexed to Irmo\nscnool district, will please take notice\nthat dn election will be held at the\nold school house within the said ter\nriiory on Saturday, April 5, 1924, tot\nthe purpose of levying an adiiittanal\nlevy Of six mills to correspond with\nthe levy in Irmo school district, of\nwhich ''he, territory is now a\npart. The palls wiit open at 7 a. m.\nand >close at 4 p. m. Bring tax re\nceipt and registration certificate.\n|y h By Order of^the county board of\neducation.\nBBS?1'*\nJ.-'O. Shealy,\nO. D. Boukhight,\nyv. M. Jacobs,\nBoard' of Manager^ for Special Elec.\nifc'. tion\nA\nCOLUMBIA' FLOWER\nHOUSE\n1244 MAIN 6T. PIIONR 7211\nCOLUMBIA\ncut flfowera for ill occasions.\nPot Plants, Bulbs and Seed.\n'VAS 1*:::.. V\nlives \u201cand friends to mourn her de- j\nparture In early youth she becamq,\na member of Nazareth \"3\u00ae. E.\nchurch, and dtferw%rds was trans\nferred to PisgalT E. T>. church, of\nv^hich she remained a faithful and\nconsistent member untl death, froij\nseveral yearp her health had been\n.impaired on account of a severe mal-'\nady from which she suffered severely,\nbut she 'bore her suffering with pa\n'\u25a0jtifcnee and Christian fortitude. She\nloved her church and attended pub-}\nlie worship when ahwas able and\nenjoyed religious services in the\nhome. She took a positive stand for\n\"the right and against the wrong, and\nher soul was vexed on account of the\nwickedness she was obliged to wit*\nj uesa on account of the position she\noccupied for the last few years. She\nwas a faithful, and ,devoted com\npanion, a fond and loving mother\nand her daughter can rise pp and call,\nher jessed. She was a .good neigh- j\nbor 6nd was loved most by those who j\nknew her! bestV \u201cBlessed are the\ndea^ who die. in the L.ord from\nhenceforth: yea, saith the Spirit, that\nthey may rest \u201cfrom their labork.\u201d\nThe funeral' and burial services\nwere held at Pisgab church and the\npastor was assisted in thege \u2018services\nby .'the Bey. A. B. Obenschain\nA large and sympathetic congregation\nof relatives and friends attended these\nservices. May tfie God of love and\nyiatcy comfort and sustain the be\nreaved-husband and daughter.\nQ. B. Shearouse. I\nPLEASANT HILL NEWS,\nThe health of this community is\ngreatly Unproved since last writing.\nThe sinking convention met with\nPleasant Hill Baptist church Sunday.\nThere was some of the best singing\nthere ever heard. Two choirs were\npresent, Pleasant Hill and New'\nBrookland. Everybody joined in the\nsong service, which was enjoyed by\nall* present. Those who were'absent\nmissed it treat. About 400 or more\n.were present.- A good number of\nchurches of Lexington County were\nrepresented including Lutheran\nMethodist and Baptist. Four profes>\nsorb were pifesentto lead the singing\u2014\nMessrs. Steele, Hall, \u2019Smith and .Tay\nlor. Rev. Mr ....Wallace opened the\n\u2022ecmvehtiQp. by: reading the last psalm,\nthen Rev. Mr. 8teele led In player\n\u2018aiid Rev.1;Sheppard dfdeed the\nconvention with prayer.'\ni'The cnventioh-will be hettflNffitbiithe,\nchurch iijext jftr\u00bbt\nSunday June. :We hope'that thib\nnext conevition will be represented\nwith more choirs; as it Is open to till\ndenomiations.\nST PETER\u2019S LUTHERAN CHURCH\nI\nSaturday, April 5, 2:80 p.\nm.i\nM _\nCatechetical clpss meets; 3 p. ri*., j\npreparatory service. .j\nSunday. April 6\u201410 a. m., Sun*!\nday school, G. B. Wingard, supers!\nintendent; 11 a. m., preaching ser-J\nvice and the administration of tho J\nHoly Communion. The public id most j\ncordially inivted to. all these Ser-\nvices. H. A. Kistler, j\n,r Pastor, j\ni 1\nmake the*hqme LOOK j\nMOKE ATTRACTUVE\nr.\nAny subjects or questions you would\nlike discusse(d in the Dispatch-News\nor any phase of Home Demonstration\u2019\nwork will bo discussed upon reecipt of\na card Or letter from you.\nThe Attractiveness of the Home\nHeaps of money spent on a home\nalone cannot make it attractive. In\na palace we rarely ever find the true\nspirit of home. The home should\nhave an individuality imparted to it\nby those who live in it. The fur\nnishing of homes should \u00abot be deco\nrative fads.\nThe home is the place far the fam\nily to rest, and it should be restful.\nThe attractive home always is.\nNothing is dainty or beautiful that\nis not clean.\nEvery article used in the home\nshould be bought to serve a distinct\npurpose both for usefulness and. deer\noration.\nGay, figured, loud wall pipe?,\nrugs and carpets should not be used.\nThey are not restful or artistic as\nthose of softer tones. j\nFurniture that is cheap and has!\nheavy carvings is hard to keep clean\nand is no longer in good taste.\nThe walls, floors and 'curtains of ad\njoining rooms should be of harmoniz\ning coWra1. *t\nAll rugs and furniture should be\nplaced straight in the room\u2014never\n\u201ccaticornered.\u201d\nPictures should be suspended by two\ncords running parallel with the\nframe and should be placed on a, level\nwith the eyes.\nj Winnie Belle Holden,:\nHome Dejn. Agt^\n/.';*1NA\u00a3 DISCHARGE. v\nNotice is hereby given ^that the un\ndeVsigned wi